      <hedline>
        <hl1>May 28-June 3; A Cheap, Long-Distance Call</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <byline class="print_byline">By STEPHEN LABATON</byline>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>Resolving years of wrangling between the nation's largest telephone companies, the federal government reached agreement on a new rate structure that will sharply reduce bills for the poorest consumers.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>Resolving years of wrangling between the nation's largest telephone companies, the federal government reached agreement on a new rate structure that will sharply reduce bills for the poorest consumers.</p>
        <p>The agreement with the Federal Communications Commission, the largest rate reduction in the agency's history, also cuts access charges that the long distance companies pay local Bell companies; the savings, if passed on to consumers, should help lower bills. The changes could lead to a flat rate for long-distance service.</p>
        <p>STEPHEN LABATON</p>
      </block>
